      <body>
         <div n="4157" type="letter"><head>4157. Robert Southey to <ref type="a" target="people.html#BowlesCaroline">Caroline Bowles</ref>, <date when="1824-03-18">18 March 1824</date>
            <note type="headnote" place="foot" resp="editors">Endorsement: N<hi rend="sup">o</hi> 49. To Miss Caroline Bowles <lb/>
               MS: British Library, Add MS 47889. ALS; 2p. <lb/>
               Unpublished. </note></head>
            
            
            <opener>  <dateline><address><placeName><ref type="m" target="places.html#Keswick">Keswick</ref></placeName></address><date when="1824-03-18"> 18 March 1824</date></dateline></opener>
            
           <p rend="indent1"> Your letter was a relief to me, – for I was afraid illness had been the cause of your silence, – &#38; it brought news of your amendment. – These hasty lines accompany a few more stanzas<note n="1" place="foot" resp="editors">Southey was beginning ‘Robin Hood’. The resulting incomplete work was published in <title>Robin Hood: a Fragment. By the Late Robert Southey, and Caroline Southey. With Other Fragments and Poems By R.S. and C.S.</title> (London, 1847), pp. [1]–36.</note> – When next you write, speak of the poem on a slip of paper by itself, &#38; let your letter have no allusion to it. I expect much amusement from keeping the secret, &#38; some advantage from it. What I write generally receives a good deal of amendment before it passes thro the press, – wherever you can mend a passage, do so. I shall soon finish the canto. – Do you describe how the <del>infant</del> &#60;boy&#62; like a pet lamb that had lost its mother – was fondled &#38; spoilt.<note n="2" place="foot" resp="editors">Caroline Bowles did not include these lines in ‘Robin Hood’.</note></p>
           <p rend="indent1"> What I said about two ounces<note n="3" place="foot" resp="editors">Southey to Caroline Bowles, 13 February 1824, Letter 4133. Southey and Bowles were corresponding through John Rickman, and thus making use of his privilege, as a senior officer of Parliament, to transmit post free of charge. However, this privilege only applied to letters of less than two ounces’ weight.</note> was only a caution, – the purse was far within the mark, &#38; came safely.</p>
          <closer>  <salute rend="indent1">God bless you</salute>
          <signed rend="indent2">  RS.</signed></closer>
         </div>
      </body>
